{{Orphan|date=January 2015}}

[[File:Palenque - Rote Königin 1.jpg|thumb|The mask of the Red Queen.]]
'''Fanny López Jiménez''' (born Tuxtla Gutiérrez, Chiapas, 1970) is a Mexican archaeologist known for her excavations at [[Palenque]], including the discovery of the [[Tomb of the Red Queen]].<ref>[http://www.mexiconewsnetwork.com/art-culture/red-queen-palenque/ The red Queen of Palenque…] ''Mexico News Network'', 2014. Retrieved 31 December 2014.</ref>

López Jiménez studied archaeology at the [[National School of Anthropology and History]] in Mexico City. She completed her first fieldwork in Lagartero near [[Comitán]] and shortly after, in 1991, performed excavation practices in Palenque, on the north side El Palacio. The remains of the Red Queen were found on 11 April 1994<ref>[http://www.discovery.com/tv-shows/other-shows/videos/assignment-discovery-palenque-red-queen/ Palenque Red Queen.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141231233022/http://www.discovery.com/tv-shows/other-shows/videos/assignment-discovery-palenque-red-queen/ |date=2014-12-31 }} Discovery Channel. Retrieved 31 December 2014.</ref> in the Temple XIII internal substructure. After further research it was López Jiménez who proposed that the identity of the formerly unknown woman was Hun K'Anleum, "Señora 1 Telaraña" ("Lady 1 Cobweb") in her article "Quién es la Reina Roja?" (Who is the Red Queen?) in ''[[Arqueología Mexicana]]''.<ref>[http://www.arqueomex.com/S2N3nREINA69.html Quién es la Reina Roja?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101012253/http://www.arqueomex.com/S2N3nREINA69.html |date=2015-01-01 }} ''Arqueología Mexicana''. Retrieved 31 December 2014.</ref>

López Jiménez is married to Hector Escobar.

