A feature of the dissemination of magnetism in the New World was its increasing association with spiritualism.{{sfn|Ramsey|1999|p=303|ps=}} By the 1830s mesmerism was making headway in the United States amongst figures like the intellectual progenitor of the [[New Thought]] movement, [[Phineas Parkhurst Quimby]], whose treatment combined verbal suggestion with touch.{{sfn|Gevitz|1997|p=261|ps=}} Quimby's most celebrated "disciple", [[Mary Baker Eddy]], would go on to found the "medico-religious hybrid", [[Christian Science]], in the latter half of the nineteenth century.{{sfn|Schoepflin|2003|pp=6&ndash;7|ps=}} In the 1840s the American spiritualist [[Andrew Jackson Davis]] sought to combine animal magnetism with spiritual beliefs and postulated that bodily health was dependent upon the unobstructed movement of the "spirit", conceived as a fluid substance, throughout the body. As with Quimby, Davis's healing practice involved the use of touch.{{sfn|Gevitz|1997|p=261|ps=}} <!-- Gevitz argues, referencing Davis's treatment of asthma by rubbing up and down the spinal column, that there may be link here with chiropractic massage; does any other source support this interpretation? -->

